< review>
It is refreshing to find a bar in Los Angels that isn't all douchey.  We stopped in early in the night to grab some pre-dinner drinks.  Happy hour is a great deal, with a good cocktail list, and pretty tasty nachos (we had to order them after we drooled over someone else's).  I'm sure it gets packed as the night goes on, but for an early drink, it's a pretty good spot in Los Angels.<//review>

< review>
Went in on a whim for my birthday and was not disappointed!
Talented and beautiful dancers, good tunes, and reasonably priced drinks.
I was a few sheets to the wind upon arrival, but I don't remember having to pay a cover charge or there even being a drink minimum, making it a really fun place to go if you're on a bit of a budget. More money to give the dancers that way! There was no line to get in, and my partner and I were able to sit right up in front of the stage.
Yes, it is small and does have a bit of a dive bar aesthetic, but that's exactly my vibe being an old punk rocker so I felt right at home.< /review>

is recommended so get some dollar bills :)

<name>Shanon Yu<//name><rate>4<//rate>< userid>
114461558056437807671</userid>
<review>Make it rain dolla dolla bills y'all!! :)

I never in a million years would have imagined that my night at an innocent Yelp hair salon event would lead me to Jumbo's Clown Room, but I'm kinda glad it did!

Jumbo's Clown Room was part 3 of our Friday night debauchery. Some of my friends suggested coming here to experience some eye candy to end our night. I didn't know what to expect since I've never even step foot into a strip club, but i walked out pleasantly entertained!

When we arrived around 12pm, there was already a long line outside. There was a parking lot with valet parking but we got lucky and found street parking nearby in the residential area. The valet attendant kept suggesting for us to get a table for $20/each person for our group of 10 people to bypass the line. We decided against it and waited about 35 minutes to get in instead. Since we were the last group to be let in, we ended up staying until the end of the night for the last remaining shows. The place itself is very small and only holds a max of 40 people or so. There's seating around the stage and limited standing room. We were able to snatch a table for 4 of us.

Once the girls started coming out to perform, I realized it really wasn't as raunchy as I thought it would be.There was no nudity but the girls did dress in pretty provocative clothing, although it wasn't anything I've never seen before at regular dance clubs.
I admired how athletic some of these girls were during their performances. Some of them did some crazy tricks on the pole and we all admired in awe of their strength.

If you want to end your night admiring sexy girls on strip poles and want to avoid the raunchiness of an actual strip club, I'd definitely suggest Jumbo's! Plus what better way to end the night than making it rain dolla bills?< /review><Pictures>None<//Pictures></record></dataset><record>
< UserId.>
111711916557288834039<//UserId.>
< user_name>
Mike Brazell<//user_name>
< date>
1449206228072< /date>
<Rate>4</Rate>< Text>
If I had to imagine the back story of Jumbo's it would go something like this:
A guy obsessed with circus clowns decides to open a burlesque bar. He buys a bunch of velvet clown paintings, hangs them up and then plugs in the big Jumbo's Clown Room sign and opens for business. It attracts a small but steady stream of tourists and proto-hipsters which is just enough to give the owner hope. The owner slides deep into debt chasing his elusive dream of running LA's hippest circus clown themed burlesque bar until his loans are sold to the Russian mob.
The mob begins laundering money through the business and plans heists and other crimes at night in the rear corner booth. Girls are smuggled, passports confiscated, and they are forced to pay for their own dance music on a rundown jukebox. Years pass, dust collects on the clowns and the upholstery wears thin. One day, the feds catch on and the original owner is offered up as a patsy. He is convicted and sent to prison and Jumbo's is reduced to a 50/50 liquor license. One of the mobsters buys a crock-pot, fills it with ketchup, and sticks it in the corner as their "kitchen," and business resumes.
Fast forward to 2000 when I move to LA and begin hearing rumors of a psuedo-strip club with a circus clown theme. Described as dingy, scary or just "gross," it is a must see LA institution. So, one weekday afternoon, I set out in search of Jumbo's and instead find bliss.
The entrance is guarded by either a bouncer or a homeless man (or both) on a broken stool. I approach slowly and hear him snoring. Pushing open the entrance I remove mirrored aviators and squint as my vision adjusts to the dark.
The dead eyes of a thousand clowns stare back at me from their black velvet prisons, wooden frames covered in a thick patina of dust. There are regular clowns, hobo clowns, rodeo clowns, and even child-molestery clowns but they are ALL sad clowns. The upholstery is a mix of duct tape and stuffing and the floor is concrete.
The thin girl sadly gyrating on stage is dressed in half bikini and half lingerie and has a scar on her belly that is either a bad C-section or a really bad stab wound. I sit down in an empty stool as the woman behind the bar yells at me in a thick Russian accent, "What do you want?"
She is a haggard 60 something but could easily pass for a really haggard 50 something. I order a margarita and she serves a bud light with an empty Styrofoam cup. I try to decline the cup but all she does is point a knotted finger at a crusty old crock pot in the corner and then makes a shooing gestures at me. I take my beer and head over, confused yet curious.
Decade old blackened and chunky ketchup slowly bubbles like a tiny La Brea Tar Pit, collecting fat flies that hover around it and preserving them for future generations. The bartender stares so I pick up a filthy ladle and stir, releasing a stench of old tomatoes and vinegar. My eyes water, I leave the cup on the counter and return to my seat as the bartender gives me a disapproving look. Perfection.
Jumbo's becomes one of my regular stops for day drinking. I eventually move to the valley and it is six years before I see the inside of the Clown Room again.
Current day:
It appears that Jumbo's may be under new management. It's cleaner, friendlier and the deco is moderately updated. I also noticed that the dancers seemed more hipster-burlesque than sad-addict and don't awkwardly approach patrons hinting at tips and adding drinks to their tabs. There was a good mix of girls and guys and everyone appeared to be under 50. My guess is that a big fan of the old bar wanted to rejuvenate it and preserve the experience but instead sterilized it and killed all that I loved about it. Still better than most LA dive bars.</Text>

Dr.. Kim is an incredible veterinarian. His office isn't fancy or modern but he performs miracles in there. I had a friend who had 2 knee surgeries performed on his  dog for thousands less than any other vet would've charged. Then a few years later his dog seemed near death but Dr.. Kim saved her again for a very reasonable price. I myself took my dog in when he had growths on his paw and he performed 2 surgeries for next to nothing and numerous follow up visits for the one time charge. His advice and diagnosis was always exactly right and sensible. He won't send you out for expensive biopsies and mri and cat scan tests.... if your looking to spend thousands on your pet go elsewhere. If your looking for great veterinary care at reasonable prices goto Alpine Animal Hospital.< /Review>

<user>102657525622757975626<//user><Name>Rudy Meza< /Name><date>1478641349233< /date>< Rating>
5<//Rating>
< Text>
So glad the taproom finally opened! Was it worth the wait? Yes! Great beer and a great space. Their Chief Peak IPA is their go to beer, but I also really love the Howler, coffee IIPA. Its a must try!

It might just be that they're newly opened, but the the bartenders are very attentive. If you're sitting there empty handed, I guarantee it won't be very long before one or two of them will ask you want you'd like to drink.

Kind of bummed you can't take your beer into the wine are and vice versa. However, the doorway to the Nook is open, do can grab a bite if you so choose. Also bit disappointed that they don't have a tv. Just one would be great. You can always just go next door to lama dog if you really need to though.

I'm just happy that another beer place has opened up in the funkzone. So many wineries here, it's nice to know there's more options now for us beer lovers!<//Text>

<Rating>5</Rating><Review>One of the most delicious Thai Food ever in Bay Area Hands Down !! Being one of many old Thai Delicacies in Berkeley, this place has been consistently serving delicious and quality Thai Foods.
Since new owners took this place, the quality of food, service and overall ambience has definitely been improved way much better.
Yellow Chicken Curry has been one of my favorites because of the coconut milk that accentuate the deliciousness of the dish.
Roasted Duck Curry is also one of my absolute favourite, the duck meat is so juicy and tender.
100% Recommended.</Review>< pics>

< time>
1618361983812</time>
<Resp>None< /Resp>< Review>
My favorite Thai Place in Berkeley for the money. I used to go here every Christmas with my family & ordered take-out regularly  over 20 years ago & the food still tastes the same. The service isn't the fastest, & I have never been there for lunch but the Green Curry is excellent, not too sweet, very herbaceous and you can add your choice of extra veggies (I like spinach) for a $1 each. I went with my friend recently, the Red Duck Curry still has the delicious, gamey greasiness I expected and wanted. Can't wait to go back for the Sticky Wings appetizer, messy & sweet but oh so delicious.</Review>

< date>
1375304270431</date>
<rate>5< /rate><text>I had a very pleasant lunch here. The service was fast, attentive, and friendly. I ordered a basil chicken rice plate, spicy and a hot Thai tea. First off, the rice was the best I've had in Berkeley. It was cooked to the point where it is soft, but not mushy. Also, there was a slight jasmine flavor that made the rice enjoyable to eat on its own, opposed to being strictly a starch to mop up left over sauce with. The basil chicken was flavorful; the meat and vegetables were fresh. The Thai hot tea managed to translate the flavor of Thai iced tea without all of the calories from the cream (free refills too). The only thing I can criticize is that my dish wasn't spicy enough, but that may be due to my love for painfully spicy food. I would highly recommend walking a few extra blocks from downtown Berkeley to have the opportunity to enjoy this gem.< /text><pics>None< /pics>< Resp>
None<//Resp>

<pictures>None</pictures><date>1546547602487< /date><username>Christian Rios< /username>< review>
I brought in my 05 corvette to get the pulley's and belt replaced. The first issue, I personally could not take the vehicle so I had my girlfriend bring in the vehicle. Although she advised the mechanic that the issue was with the belt, the serviceman tried selling her a timing chain. Once she got her father involved, they agreed that it was belt. They told us that it would take 3 days to repair but it took 6 days (total) for them to return the vehicle. They kept promising me that the vehicle would be ready by the end of the day, but would push the date back. I finally got the car back and drove the car for a night and noticed (on the next day) that there was a loud tap under the hood. When I inspected the pulley's, the mechanic did not tighten the bolt on the harmonic balancer pulley (causing damage). The vehicle was brought in and took them 2 days to fix. The car was running well, however, the tension of the belt was not correct and it became loose again. Unfortunately, since I only drive the vehicle on weekends, the problem became more apparent once the warranty expired. I have only driven the vehicle for 200+ miles within the last 3 months. I would not recommend this auto repair shop at all. This shop does not provide quality work (despite the high cost of the repair + delays) and are unprofessional.< /review>

<UserId.>114112511156992730202<//UserId.><name>windell jennings</name><Date>1530340744325< /Date><rating>1</rating>< Text>
I frequented this business at one time once a week but the poor customer service as well as the cheapness they show in providing condiments has me never returning after today. this brings me to reason of this post.  My order for today was very simple..Two too item combos (Prawns & oyster) & (Prawns & Sole) and a large Sole dinner. I was asked if I wanted bread included in the said dinner..I said yes..I was told 20 min it would ready. Upon my arrival 35 mins later my food was not prepared. I was asked to pay for the food which I did and then waited for an additional 15 min.  Th meals were poorly prepared as well as the portion were abnormally small. In addition because i was on lunch i didn't get a chance to look at the food. When my co-workers and I were able to eat the food we found only bread in one meal and even sadder two ketchup packages one tartar sauce for each meal and one tea spoon full of hot sauce in a container.... smh...The food is very pricey and the taste has never been above a 5 but its locations is ideal to my employer.  The Wonder bread they use cost a dollar a loaf. I was disappointed for the final time and will not be return...$74.18 for three meals and i got it to go and did get freak'n bread. Be advise</Text>

< text>
This place has a large selection of couches but not much else. A lot of the furniture is in kind of rough shape, but the discounts are very substantial. It's Restoration Hardware though, so even with a big discount it's still very expensive. The big issue with this store is that it really isn't much of a store. <Review>99 Ranch Market has been in the Asian supermarket for a long time, but it doesn't seem like it's keeping up with some of the competition.  Look at H-Mart.  The stores on the outside keeps up with the times and looks nice and presentable.  It's not necessarily 99 ranch's fault but it doesn't give a good impression.  Go up and down the aisles and you see things in cardboard boxes and not nicely displayed.  The place looks dated.  The glass displays for the meats and fish look dingy.  The benefit of the store looking the way it does, keeps the prices low, but it doesn't give confidence in how sanitary things are or are not.</Review>< Resp>

< Review>
LOVE the 99Ranch!  It's across the street from the car dealership I have most my car stuff done....so I wander over here often to stock up on VitaSoy, noodles, Aloe drinks, ice coffee and such.  Big GIANT produce section with really great looking Fuji apples, dragonfruit, mangos,etc.

Until a few years ago, this was the ONLY 99Ranch in San Diego.  I think I have seen two or three others now (Balboa?).  LA has several dozen of these places.  Parking here can be sketchy.  There is LOTS of parking (All four sides of the store!)...but the spaces are striped pretty small.< /Review>

< UserId.>
105472217198867195667<//UserId.>
<Name>Odette Nudera<//Name>< time>
1616265943943< /time>
<Rating>3< /Rating>< Review>
A good Oriental supermarket for everyone, a bit more pricey than others,  With a good selection of Asian goods & ingredients.  They have the Pandemic Safety Code compliance in place, social distancing markers on the floor,  plastic screen partitions at checkouts,  all staff & customers are required to wear a face mask while in the store. The produce section stocked well w unique and hard to find ethnic fruits and vegetables. The meat section is also stocked with all selections of cuts and hard to find organ meats for that unique recipe or menu.  Now,  the Seafood section is another world in its own.  First of all, the very strong & pungent odor & smell of bad fish & all other seafood,  although items on display seems OK and not bad or rotten. This area is always wet & noisy, busy with customers milling around, looking to make their choices.  I make a very quick trip here and pick up my calamari (squid) from the frozen section & head away from the bad & unpleasant odor from the  area.  Also has a Take - Out Cooked Food counter at the front of the store that's got a great selection of Asian cuisine.  Ranch 99 is one of my stops for Asian grocery Shopping as their inventory is well stocked & organized.  Hopefully, they can improve the seafood area by proper,  professional cleaning & sanitizing for the good,  safety & hygienic environment for customers & employees.   Compliance with the health, sanitation & safety codes of the Health Dept. must be maintained.<//Review>

< Review>
Asian Market with an Asian Parking lot (park in the back or snag a spot on the street, the only thing worse than Asian Parking lots are Asian Drivers - trust me... im Asian)
My favorite service from this market is their fish cleaning and fry service.
Just make sure to drive home with the windows down ( again, trust me on this one 100 %)

4 stars because:

<Review>I love this place....  But it's getting old and janky.

I primary go here for the big selection of Asian packaged groceries.

Even though the produce is cheap, majority of the time it's a little dingy or picked through.

Sometimes I'll buy fresh meat and seafood from here, but usually the frozen stuff.  It's easier to just grab and go.

< review>
For the Asian food selection of this store are with the widest variety of selection for Chinese, Japanese and Vietnamese fresh vegetables/fruits, canned, dried and preserved containers.  Fresh soy milk, tofu, noodles, ready to eat Asian meals and similar cow poison liquids are in coolers/freezers.

A hot foods smorgasbord of Asian food choices are here for dining in or taking out for picnics, church, school or parties.

Also find rare hard to find pricey liquors: Brandy, whiskey, sake, Korean liquors and red wines.

Pick something to try,. Joy of trying a new cultural performance.<//review>

<UserId.>116068631758069036890<//UserId.>< review>
Unlike other Asian markets (Linda Vista Rd comes to mind), the employees here are available and willing to help.

Found store layout easy to maneuver and easily locate items. Hot food service looked good, as did bakery & pastries section.

Will go out of my way to shop here instead of the other markets l used to go to.</review>

< Review>
Good place to get those Asian ingredients that are hard to find at most Western chain supermarkets. However, I've noticed lately their produce looks a bit old (wilted greens, mushy cucumbers, erc). They need to step up their game or their competitors (e.g. Zion Market) are going to catch up. Also their prices for Asian style cookware and accessories are quite high.</Review>

<rating>3< /rating><review>This store is easy to reach, but the parking spaces are small. Enjoy the fish fountain out front before you enter. Once inside, expect to find occasional deals, while usually spending more on similar items found at nearby larger Asian grocery stores. There's a fish market and a produce area. The isles are full with a huge selection, and seasonal items are available near the check stands. It's good to visit stores off your beaten path, to see what's out there... But realize there are other options down the street.</review><pics>None</pics>< response>

< Text>
Very busy on weekends and parking is a train wreck waiting to happen.  Asian groceries are plentiful, many varieties of fresh vegetables and fruits, well stocked sauces, canned goods, baked goods, snacks, etc. Aisles are tiny so shopping can be an uncomfortable experience. Go when it's quiet.  Park and drive defensively.< /Text>

Dare I say it? I enjoy this place more than Zion Market and H Mart. There are lots of prepared foods to choose from for quick meals. I also found cooked freeze dried crawfish at 50% off (1 lb totaled to $5). Who does that in Cali? Guess what else, hearty Strawberries were 99 cents a lb. I know, right? Well, this is my second time shopping here and not only are staff kind and helpful, but the shopping experience was engaging and enjoyable. This is my new spot for groceries. Best place in San Diego to buy Asian food and supplies.  They usually have decent sales on peanut oil so you can stock up. Prices on vegetables and fruits sometimes beat the regular supermarket specials.

<rating>2<//rating>< review>
When did it get so bad? Has it always been this bad and I never noticed? Well one day I got woke and maybe it was right around the time Zion opened up, but it‚Äôs been spiraling for years before that even.

Parking, forget it, I wouldn‚Äôt steal and car just to come here. The damage your car will take from the pummeling of doors is crazy, let alone the bad drivers. Literally I got to the point where I wouldn‚Äôt even parking the shopping center, but walk from nearby lots. The lot itself is basically a grease stain, chewing gum cemetery with cigarette butts imbedded with tumbleweeds separating things.

I do like how the isles are consistent and not some quadrant-ed maze. The staff is decidedly terse, but the prices are still decent which brings people. The seafood tanks are cool because nothing beats picking your food for freshness. It is an Asian market unlike Seafood City which is specifically Filipino, so here I often get Asian pantry items, produce and seafood. Their thai curry selection is better than most, I also get my squid tentacles here (I like whole squid, but the tentacles are the best part), snack at the food court. I‚Äôm only writing this as a farewell as I will be going to the Clairemont location from now on, sorry not sorry, you should move to there too.< /review>

< review>
Usually 99 ranch markets can't get more than three stars from me because they, despite being Chinese, they are crowded with people and shelves, dirty, reek of various things in various states of premeditated decay.

But this one, despite being an older store, is freshly remodeled and actually makes a passing grade in cleanliness and scalability in the aisles. Same 99 ranch market prices and goods. Also has both OO Tea for boba and the equally excellent Sam Woo for a reasonably priced meal.<//review>

<user_id>103124858800019566456<//user_id><name>Adrienne Garcia< /name>< Date>
1439946565830< /Date>
<rating>5</rating>< Text>
Top 3 things I love about 99 Ranch:

1 - the boba drinks at Sau Voi Deli... Try avocado, lychee, or taro!  They also have various jelly drinks and fresh sugar cane juice available.

2 - the daily special at the "food court" inside the store, near the bakery.  Sometimes it's fish, sometimes it's pork ... but it's always cheaper than a combo and YUMMY!! I particularly like their Chinese beef stew over rice!

3 - If you buy a whole fish from the butcher, they will clean, cut (or not), and fry it for you!</Text>

< Review>
Top 3 things I love about 99 Ranch:

1 - the boba drinks at Sau Voi Deli... Try avocado, lychee, or taro!  They also have various jelly drinks and fresh sugar cane juice available.

2 - the daily special at the "food court" inside the store, near the bakery.  Sometimes it's fish, sometimes it's pork ... but it's always cheaper than a combo and YUMMY!! I particularly like their Chinese beef stew over rice!

3 - If you buy a whole fish from the butcher, they will clean, cut (or not), and fry it for you!< /Review>
